      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "By the great, scaly maw of the Goblins! A p-value of 0.06, you say? That's like finding a perfectly good pile of shiny, slightly rusty trinkets, but the Goblin Elder insists they aren't *quite* valuable enough for the big hoard. It's a thorny bit of statistical weeds, but I can try to untangle it for you, though my mind is currently occupied by whether the local goblin tribe prefers pickled fungus or slightly charred swamp moss for their midday snack.\n\nThe core issue, my friend, is the arbitrary nature of the threshold, usually set at $\\alpha = 0.05$. When you get $p = 0.06$, it means that *if* there were truly no effect—if the null hypothesis were true, like if the goblins were all just pretending to be clever when they're actually just hungry—there's a 6% chance you'd see a trend as strong as the one you observed, purely by random chance.\n\nThe theoretical weight of that 0.05 cutoff is that it represents a pre-agreed-upon level of risk you are willing to accept for making a Type I",
      "source": "target",
